## 📐 Auto Layout Rules

All frames in Figma must use **Auto Layout** — do not use manual positioning.

### Required Settings

| Element Type | Direction | Gap | Padding |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Full screen frame (`.phone`) | Vertical | 0 | 0 |
| Navigation bar | Horizontal | 0 (space between) | 12px top/bottom, 16px left/right |
| Card list / list sections | Vertical | 12px | 16px |
| Card / row item | Horizontal | 8–12px | 12–16px |
| Button | Horizontal | 8px | 12px top/bottom, 20px left/right |
| Header section | Vertical | 8px | 16px |

### Rules

* Set **Hug contents** on components that wrap content (e.g., badges, buttons, tags)
* Set **Fill container** on items that should stretch horizontally inside a list
* Set **Fixed** width/height only on the root `.phone` frame (`390 × 844`)
* Do NOT use absolute positioning for layout — only for decorative overlays
* Child spacing must use Auto Layout `gap`, not manual margins

---

## 📜 Scroll Behavior Rules

Some pages have content that exceeds the fixed `844px` frame height. These pages must be set up for vertical scrolling.

### Pages That Require Scroll

The following pages should have scroll enabled:

* `leaderboard` — long player list
* `history` — match history list
* `bookings` — booking cards list
* `score-tracking` — detailed score breakdown
* `my-lobbies` — lobby card list
* `lobby-hub` — lobby discovery list
* `session-summary` — post-match summary
* `player-feedback` — feedback form

### Figma Scroll Setup

For any scrollable page:

1. Set the **Frame** (`.phone`) to `390 × 844` — this is the viewport, do not change it
2. Set **Clip content: ON** on the frame
3. Set **Overflow: Vertical scroll** on the frame
4. Place all content inside a **child Auto Layout frame** with:
   * Width: `390px`
   * Height: `Hug contents` (this grows taller than 844px)
   * Direction: Vertical
   * Gap: match the design spec

### HTML Equivalent

The HTML implementation must match the scroll behavior:

```css
.phone {
  width: 390px;
  height: 844px;
  overflow-y: auto;
  overflow-x: hidden;
}

.phone-content {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  min-height: 100%;
  /* height grows beyond 844px for scrollable pages */
}
```

> Fixed elements like `BottomNav` must use `position: sticky; bottom: 0` in HTML and be pinned to the bottom of the viewport frame in Figma using **Pin to bottom**.

